Author-Name: Monica Martinez-Bravo
Title: The Role of Local Officials in New Democracies: Evidence from Indonesia
Abstract: This paper shows that the body of appointed officials that a new
democracy inherits from the previous regime is a key determinant
of the extent of electoral fraud and clientelistic spending in new
democracies. I develop a model that predicts that appointed officials
have stronger incentives to influence voters during national level
elections because of their career concerns. I test the implications
of the model using data from Indonesia's transition to democracy.
Both the pattern of alignment of electoral results between village
and district levels and the pattern of subsequent turnover of
appointed village heads corroborate the predictions of the model.
