Author-Name: Rodolfo E. Manuelli
Author-Name: Ananth Seshadri
Title: Frictionless Technology Diffusion: The Case of Tractors
Abstract: Many new technologies display long adoption lags, and this is often
interpreted as evidence of frictions inconsistent with the standard
neoclassical model. We study the diffusion of the tractor in American
agriculture between 1910 and 1960-a well-known case of slow
diffusion-and show that the speed of adoption was consistent with
the predictions of a simple neoclassical growth model. The reason for
the slow rate of diffusion was that tractor quality kept improving over
this period and, more importantly, that only when wages increased
did it become relatively unprofitable to operate the alternative, labor-intensive, horse technology.
